04255nam a22006495i 9780823291519DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20222006nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232915197 a10.1515/97808232915192doi  a(DE-B1597)566002  a(OCoLC)1306541390  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0040202bisacsh1 aHaddox, Thomas F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFears and Fascinations :bRepresenting Catholicism in the American South /cThomas F. Haddox. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (236 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1 Catholic Miscegenations: The Cultural Legacy of Les Cenelles -- t2 Medieval Yearnings: A Catholicism for Whites in Nineteenth-Century Southern Literature -- t3 The Pleasures of Decadence: Catholicism in Kate Chopin, Carson McCullers, and Anne Rice -- t4 Agrarian Catholics: The Catholic Turn in Southern Literature -- t5 Toward Catholicism as Lifestyle: Walker Percy, John Kennedy Toole, and Rebecca Wells -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis innovative book charts what has been a largely unexplored literary landscape, looking at the work of such diverse writers as the gens de couleur libre poets of antebellum New Orleans, Kate Chopin, Mark Twain, Carson McCullers, Margaret Mitchell, Allen Tate, Caroline Gordon, Flannery O'Connor, Walker Percy, and John Kennedy Toole. Haddox shows that Catholicism and its Church have always been a presence, albeit in different ways, in the southern cultural tradition. For some, Catholicism has been associated with miscegenation and with the political aspirations of African-Americans; for others, it has served as the model for the feudal and patriarchal society that some southern whites sought to establish; for still others, it has presented a gorgeous aesthetic spectacle associated with decadence and homoeroticism; and for still others, it has marked a "idian, do-it-yourself "lifestyle" attractive for its lack of concern with southern anxieties about honor. By focusing on the shifting and contradictory ways Catholicism has signified within southern literature and culture, Fears and Fascinations contributes to a more nuanced understanding of American and southern literary and cultural history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082322521740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329151940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823291519423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823291519/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK